1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,494
Peptide bonds link amino acids into proteins — from hemoglobin in your blood to collagen in your skin.

2
00:00:06,494 --> 00:00:09,551
This one bond builds life's molecular machinery.

3
00:00:09,551 --> 00:00:11,016
Let's see how it forms.

4
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:17,927
Every amino acid has two reactive ends: an electron-rich amine and an electron-poor carbonyl.

5
00:00:17,927 --> 00:00:20,923
The nitrogen's lone pair makes it a nucleophile

6
00:00:20,923 --> 00:00:23,664
naturally drawn toward the carbonyl carbon.

7
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:28,588
Quantum chemistry explains this through orbital overlap.

8
00:00:28,588 --> 00:00:30,639
The nitrogen lone pair, the HOMO

9
00:00:30,639 --> 00:00:33,779
donates electrons into the carbonyl's empty LUMO.

10
00:00:33,779 --> 00:00:37,240
This frontier orbital interaction drives the reaction.

11
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:42,806
But there's a catch: an energy barrier of about eighty kilojoules per mole.

12
00:00:42,806 --> 00:00:46,780
The Gibbs and Arrhenius equations show that without a catalyst

13
00:00:46,780 --> 00:00:49,280
this reaction is far too slow in water.

14
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:54,230
When the barrier is overcome, nitrogen attacks the carbonyl carbon

15
00:00:54,230 --> 00:00:55,730
sharing its electrons.

16
00:00:55,730 --> 00:01:00,896
Pi electrons shift onto oxygen as atoms rearrange into a tetrahedral intermediate.

17
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:05,094
Proton transfers then trigger water's departure.

18
00:01:05,094 --> 00:01:08,317
What remains is the new carbon-nitrogen amide bond

19
00:01:08,317 --> 00:01:10,831
and the geometry flattens into a plane.

20
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:14,461
The resulting peptide bond is special.

21
00:01:14,461 --> 00:01:17,571
Resonance gives it partial double-bond character

22
00:01:17,571 --> 00:01:19,709
locking the backbone into a rigid

23
00:01:19,709 --> 00:01:22,560
planar shape that defines protein structure.

24
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:27,460
In cells, ribosomes use ATP to forge twenty peptide bonds per second.

25
00:01:27,460 --> 00:01:31,984
This chemistry also enables peptide drugs like insulin, GLP-1 agonists

26
00:01:31,984 --> 00:01:33,536
and cancer therapeutics.

27
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:37,026
From orbital overlap to resonance stabilization

28
00:01:37,026 --> 00:01:40,117
the peptide bond is where physics meets biology.

29
00:01:40,117 --> 00:01:43,788
Understanding it unlocks protein engineering, drug design

30
00:01:43,788 --> 00:01:45,591
and the foundations of life.
